    <p>Genealogy research is, by its nature, an imperfect process. We want to be completely transparent about this:</p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>Historical records are incomplete.</strong> Many records have been lost, damaged, or never created in the first place. Particularly before civil registration began in England and Wales in 1837, records become significantly sparser.</li>
        <li><strong>Records can be ambiguous.</strong> Common names, spelling variations, transcription errors in original documents, and indexing mistakes in databases can all lead to difficulties in identifying the correct individuals.</li>
        <li><strong>Some lines will go further than others.</strong> It is normal for some branches of a family tree to be traceable back many generations while others hit dead ends much sooner.</li>
        <li><strong>AI-assisted research is not infallible.</strong> While we use AI tools to help cross-reference and validate findings, these tools can make errors. All AI-generated suggestions are reviewed before inclusion in your final results.</li>
